{"type":"message","id":"2b1592ba","parentId":"806858fc","timestamp":"2026-03-17T02:23:25.762Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"toolu_vrtx_017bmnwgv7zazft3i3sww5d1","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"# Methodology\n\nFollowing the established research framework for zero-shot fault diagnosis in complex industrial systems, this section provides an exhaustive technical breakdown of the proposed CLIP-Enhanced Semantic Manifold Diffusion (CESM-Diff) model. The methodology is specifically designed to transcend the limitations of traditional discrete attribute-based zero-shot learning (ZSL) by leveraging the continuous latent spaces offered by large-scale vision-language pre-training and the high-fidelity generation capabilities of dual-path diffusion probabilistic models.\n\nWe structure this methodology into six core components: (1) an overall framework overview illustrating how each module contributes to the end-to-end pipeline; (2) a formal mathematical definition of the zero-shot fault diagnosis problem in the context of continuous semantic manifolds; (3) the extraction mechanism for high-dimensional fault semantics using the CLIP text encoder; (4) the detailed architecture of the Dual-Path Semantic Diffusion (DPSD) model; (5) the Semantic Manifold Interpolation (SMI) strategy for augmenting the feature space; and (6) the multi-objective optimization framework involving Attribute Consistency Loss.\n\n## 3.1 Overall Framework\n\nThe proposed CESM-Diff model is architected as an integrated pipeline comprising four tightly coupled modules that collectively enable zero-shot fault diagnosis through semantic-guided feature synthesis. This section provides a bird's-eye view of how these modules interact during both the training and inference phases before delving into the mathematical details of each component in subsequent subsections.\n\n**Module I: CLIP-Based Semantic Encoding.** The first stage transforms human-readable fault descriptions into dense, continuous semantic embeddings. For every fault category—whether seen during training or reserved as unseen for evaluation—a domain-specific textual prompt is constructed following a structured template that encodes physical characteristics, frequency signatures, and operational impacts. These prompts are then forwarded through the frozen CLIP text encoder $E_{text}$, yielding normalized $k$-dimensional embedding vectors that reside on a unit hypersphere. The resulting semantic manifold inherits the rich relational structure learned during CLIP's large-scale contrastive pre-training, ensuring that physically similar faults are mapped to proximate regions in the embedding space.\n\n**Module II: Dual-Path Semantic Diffusion (DPSD).** The core generative engine of CESM-Diff operates via two synchronized diffusion processes. The feature path progressively corrupts real fault signals with Gaussian noise during training, while the semantic path simultaneously perturbs the corresponding CLIP embeddings according to a coordinated noise schedule. A novel Cross-Path Attention (CPA) mechanism bridges these two paths at every denoising layer, enabling the model to dynamically query the semantic manifold and inject fault-specific information into the feature reconstruction process. During inference, the reverse diffusion process starts from pure Gaussian noise and iteratively denoises it under the guidance of a target semantic vector, synthesizing high-fidelity features for any fault class—including those never observed during training.\n\n**Module III: Semantic Manifold Interpolation (SMI).** To address the sparsity of the semantic space—particularly in the regions corresponding to unseen fault classes—the SMI module generates virtual semantic embeddings via Spherical Linear Interpolation (Slerp) between pairs of seen-class embeddings. These interpolated semantics are then passed through the trained DPSD to produce virtual fault features that populate the transitional regions of the feature manifold. A manifold consistency loss ensures that interpolation in the semantic space yields smooth, physically plausible transitions in the feature space, thereby enriching the training set for the downstream classifier.\n\n**Module IV: Attribute Consistency Constraint.** The final module closes the semantic feedback loop by employing a pre-trained attribute regressor $R$ that maps generated features back into the semantic space. The Attribute Consistency Loss (ACL) penalizes any discrepancy between the input semantic condition and the regressor's prediction on the synthesized feature, ensuring that every generated sample faithfully encodes the fault characteristics specified by its conditioning vector.\n\n**Training Pipeline.** During training, Modules I and IV are pre-computed or pre-trained and then frozen, while Modules II and III are jointly optimized under a composite loss function $\\mathcal{L}_{total} = \\mathcal{L}_{diff} + \\eta \\mathcal{L}_{ACL} + \\sigma \\mathcal{L}_{SMI}$. The training alternates between standard diffusion denoising steps and periodic ACL evaluation steps to balance generation quality with semantic fidelity.\n\n**Inference Pipeline.** At inference time, the pipeline proceeds sequentially: (1) CLIP encodes the textual description of each unseen fault class; (2) the DPSD generates synthetic features via classifier-free guided reverse diffusion conditioned on these embeddings; (3) optionally, SMI-augmented features are generated to further enrich the feature pool; and (4) a standard supervised classifier is trained on the union of real seen-class features and synthetic unseen-class features, enabling generalized zero-shot fault diagnosis.\n\nThe key mathematical notations used throughout this paper are summarized in Table I.\n\n## 3.2 Problem Definition and Mathematical Formalization\n\nZero-shot fault diagnosis (ZSFD) represents a challenging paradigm where a diagnostic system must generalize its knowledge from a set of \"seen\" fault categories to a disjoint set of \"unseen\" categories without having observed a single training sample from the latter. This problem is inherently one of domain generalization and knowledge transfer, mediated through a shared semantic space.\n\n### 3.2.1 Feature and Label Spaces\nLet the input space be denoted by $\\mathcal{X} \\subset \\mathbb{R}^d$, representing raw or pre-processed sensor signals (e.g., vibration time-series, acoustic emissions, or pressure readings) transformed into a $d$-dimensional feature space. The set of seen classes is denoted by $\\mathcal{Y}_s = \\{y_1, y_2, \\dots, y_S\\}$, and the set of unseen classes is $\\mathcal{Y}_u = \\{u_1, u_2, \\dots, u_U\\}$. A fundamental constraint of ZSFD is that $\\mathcal{Y}_s \\cap \\mathcal{Y}_u = \\emptyset$.\n\nThe training dataset $\\mathcal{D}_{tr} = \\{(x_i^s, y_i^s)\\}_{i=1}^{N_s}$ consists of $N_s$ labeled samples where $x_i^s \\in \\mathcal{X}$ and $y_i^s \\in \\mathcal{Y}_s$. The ultimate goal is to learn a classifier $f: \\mathcal{X} \\to \\mathcal{Y}_u$ (in the pure zero-shot setting) or $f: \\mathcal{X} \\to \\mathcal{Y}_s \\cup \\mathcal{Y}_u$ (in the generalized zero-shot setting, GZSFD).\n\n### 3.2.2 The Continuous Semantic Manifold\nTo bridge the gap between $\\mathcal{Y}_s$ and $\\mathcal{Y}_u$, we introduce a semantic space $\\mathcal{S}$. In conventional ZSL, $\\mathcal{S} \\subset \\{0, 1\\}^A$ is often a discrete space of $A$ binary attributes. In CESM-Diff, we redefine $\\mathcal{S} \\subset \\mathbb{R}^k$ as a continuous, high-dimensional semantic manifold.\n\nEach class $c \\in \\mathcal{Y}_s \\cup \\mathcal{Y}_u$ is mapped to a unique semantic representation $s_c \\in \\mathcal{S}$. This mapping is achieved through a semantic extraction function $\\Phi: \\mathcal{T} \\to \\mathcal{S}$, where $\\mathcal{T}$ is the space of natural language descriptions. Thus, $s_c = \\Phi(T_c)$, where $T_c$ is a detailed textual prompt describing the physical characteristics, frequency components, and operational impacts of fault $c$. Mathematically, this manifold is regularized such that local proximity in $\\mathcal{S}$ corresponds to physical similarity in the vibration signatures of $\\mathcal{X}$.\n\n### 3.2.3 The Generative Objective\nThe core strategy of our methodology is to learn a conditional generative distribution $p(x | s)$. By training a model on seen classes $(x^s, s_{y^s})$, we aim to capture the underlying conditional manifold such that we can sample synthetic features $\\hat{x}^u \\sim p(x | s_u)$ for unseen classes. This effectively converts the ZSFD problem into a standard supervised classification problem in the feature space $\\mathcal{X}$. The objective is to minimize the discrepancy between the synthesized distribution $p_{\\theta}(x | s)$ and the true but unknown distribution of industrial fault features.\n\nFormally, we define the log-likelihood objective for the generative model as:\n$$ \\mathcal{L}_{LL} = \\mathbb{E}_{x \\sim p_{data}(x), s \\sim p(s)} [\\log p_{\\theta}(x|s)] $$\nwhere $p_{\\theta}(x|s)$ is modeled as a reverse diffusion process. To ensure the generated features are discriminative, we further constrain the entropy of the conditional distribution $H(y|x)$ over the synthesized samples.\n\n## 3.3 CLIP Text Encoder for Semantic Extraction\n\nThe quality of knowledge transfer in ZSFD is strictly bounded by the expressiveness of the semantic space $\\mathcal{S}$. Hand-crafted attributes (e.g., \"high vibration,\" \"bearing wear\") suffer from subjectivity, sparsity, and a lack of inter-attribute correlation. To resolve this, we employ the Contrastive Language-Image Pre-training (CLIP) text encoder as our semantic backbone.\n\n### 3.3.1 Domain-Specific Prompt Engineering\nThe raw input to the CLIP encoder is a professional diagnostic prompt $\\text{Prompt}_y$. Unlike generic ZSL, industrial faults require high precision. We define a prompt template:\n$$ \\text{Prompt}_y = \\text{\"Industrial [MACHINE] fault: [CLASS NAME]. Characteristics include [C1], [C2], and [C3].\"} $$\nFor instance, a \"Ball Bearing Inner Race Fault\" might be described as: *\"Industrial rotating machinery fault: Inner race bearing wear. Characteristics include high-frequency periodic impacts, fundamental train frequency modulation, and increased operating temperature.\"*\n\nAs illustrated in **Fig. 1**, the prompt engineering process transforms discrete class labels into a rich hierarchy of textual descriptions. This hierarchical mapping allows the model to inherit structural knowledge from the pre-trained CLIP space, which has already learned the relationships between physical concepts like \"wear,\" \"impact,\" and \"vibration.\"\n\n### 3.3.2 Encoder Architecture\nThe CLIP text encoder $E_{text}$ is a Transformer-based architecture. For a given prompt $T_y$ consisting of $L$ tokens, the encoder processes the sequence:\n1.  **Tokenization**: The text is converted into a sequence of Byte-Pair Encoding (BPE) tokens.\n2.  **Embedding Layer**: Tokens are mapped to initial vectors $v \\in \\mathbb{R}^{d_{model}}$.\n3.  **Transformer Blocks**: $E_{text}$ consists of $12$ layers of multi-head self-attention. For each layer $l$:\n    $$ \\text{Attention}(Q, K, V) = \\text{softmax}\\left(\\frac{QK^T}{\\sqrt{d_k}}\\right)V $$\n    where $Q, K, V$ are the query, key, and value projections of the hidden states.\n4.  **Pooling and Projection**: The hidden state of the `[EOS]` (End of Sentence) token is extracted and projected into a joint multimodal space of dimension $k = 512$ or $1024$.\n\nThe final output is the normalized semantic embedding:\n$$ s_y = \\frac{E_{text}(T_y)}{\\|E_{text}(T_y)\\|_2} $$\n\n### 3.3.3 Manifold Properties\nThe resulting CLIP embeddings $s_y$ reside on a hypersphere. Crucially, these embeddings capture the linguistic and physical relationships between faults. For example, the cosine similarity between \"Inner Race Fault\" and \"Outer Race Fault\" is significantly higher than between \"Inner Race Fault\" and \"Stator Unbalance.\" This structured continuity is the foundation for the subsequent diffusion and interpolation processes. We observe that the local curvature of the semantic manifold in the CLIP space correlates with the difficulty of distinguishing between fault types in the physical domain.\n\n## 3.4 Dual-Path Semantic Diffusion (DPSD)\n\nThe proposed DPSD architecture is the central engine of CESM-Diff. Unlike standard diffusion models that treat the condition as a static vector, DPSD treats the semantic embedding as a dynamic path that evolves alongside the feature. The overall system architecture is depicted in **Fig. 2**, showing the interaction between the feature denoising path and the semantic conditioning path.\n\n### 3.4.1 Mathematical Foundation of Diffusion\nWe define two concurrent diffusion processes: one in the feature space $\\mathcal{X}$ and one in the semantic space $\\mathcal{S}$.\n\n**Forward Diffusion (Noise Addition):**\nWe define a Markov chain that gradually adds Gaussian noise to the data following a variance schedule $\\beta_1, \\dots, \\beta_T$:\n$$ q(x_t | x_{t-1}) = \\mathcal{N}(x_t; \\sqrt{1-\\beta_t} x_{t-1}, \\beta_t \\mathbf{I}) $$\n$$ q(s_t | s_{t-1}) = \\mathcal{N}(s_t; \\sqrt{1-\\beta_t^s} s_{t-1}, \\beta_t^s \\mathbf{I}) $$\nThrough the reparameterization trick, we can express $x_t$ and $s_t$ at any timestep $t$ directly from the ground truth $x_0$ and $s_0$:\n$$ x_t = \\sqrt{\\bar{\\alpha}_t} x_0 + \\sqrt{1-\\bar{\\alpha}_t} \\epsilon, \\quad \\epsilon \\sim \\mathcal{N}(0, \\mathbf{I}) $$\n$$ s_t = \\sqrt{\\bar{\\alpha}_t^s} s_0 + \\sqrt{1-\\bar{\\alpha}_t^s} \\epsilon^s, \\quad \\epsilon^s \\sim \\mathcal{N}(0, \\mathbf{I}) $$\nwhere $\\alpha_t = 1 - \\beta_t$ and $\\bar{\\alpha}_t = \\prod_{i=1}^t \\alpha_i$. The noise schedule $\\beta_t$ is typically linear or cosine-based, ensuring that the transition from signal to pure noise is smooth and tractable.\n\n### 3.4.2 Reverse Diffusion (The Denoising Path)\nThe goal of the model is to learn several denoising functions. However, instead of independent denoising, we synchronize them:\n$$ p_{\\theta}(x_{t-1} | x_t, s_t) = \\mathcal{N}(x_{t-1}; \\mu_{\\theta}(x_t, s_t, t), \\Sigma_{\\theta}(x_t, s_t, t)) $$\nThe mean $\\mu_{\\theta}$ is parameterized using the predicted noise $\\epsilon_{\\theta}(x_t, s_t, t)$:\n$$ \\mu_{\\theta}(x_t, s_t, t) = \\frac{1}{\\sqrt{\\alpha_t}} \\left( x_t - \\frac{\\beta_t}{\\sqrt{1-\\bar{\\alpha}_t}} \\epsilon_{\\theta}(x_t, s_t, t) \\right) $$\n\n### 3.4.3 Detailed Model Architecture\nThe DPSD backbone consists of the following technical layers:\n1.  **Temporal Embedding**: The timestep $t$ is encoded using sinusoidal positional embeddings or a Learned Fourier Feature (LFF) layer to map the scalar $t$ to a high-dimensional vector $e_t \\in \\mathbb{R}^{d_{emb}}$.\n2.  **Semantic Projection**: The noisy semantic $s_t$ is passed through a Multi-Layer Perceptron (MLP) with GELU activation to align its dimensionality with the feature hidden states.\n3.  **Cross-Path Attention (CPA)**: This is the critical innovation. At each layer of the denoising network, we compute an attention map between the feature hidden states $H_x$ and the semantic hidden states $H_s$:\n    $$ Q = W_q H_x, \\quad K = W_k H_s, \\quad V = W_v H_s $$\n    $$ \\text{CPA}(H_x, H_s) = \\text{softmax}\\left(\\frac{QK^T}{\\sqrt{d_k}} + M\\right)V $$\n    where $M$ is a causal mask (if applicable). This allows the denoising process to \"look\" at the semantic manifold and decide which fault attributes are most relevant at the current noise level $t$.\n4.  **ResNet Blocks**: Each layer incorporates residual blocks to facilitate gradient flow and prevent vanishing gradients during the deep denoising process.\n5.  **Skip Connections**: Like a standard U-Net, high-resolution information is preserved via skip connections, which is particularly important for maintaining the fine-grained signal characteristics of industrial sensors.\n\n### 3.4.4 Adaptive Guidance\nDuring inference, we utilize classifier-free guidance to enhance the fidelity of the generated samples. The predicted noise is a linear combination:\n$$ \\hat{\\epsilon}_{\\theta}(x_t, s_0, t) = (1+w) \\epsilon_{\\theta}(x_t, s_0, t) - w \\epsilon_{\\theta}(x_t, \\emptyset, t) $$\nwhere $w$ is the guidance scale. This forces the model to stay close to the semantic condition $s_0$, effectively steering the generation toward the desired fault class regions.\n\n## 3.5 Semantic Manifold Interpolation (SMI)\n\nIndustrial faults often exhibit \"inter-class\" behavior. For instance, a bearing race fault might share characteristics with both purely \"Normal\" signals and \"Severe Damage\" signals. To better cover the feature space, we propose Semantic Manifold Interpolation (SMI), the workflow of which is shown in **Fig. 3**.\n\n### 3.5.1 Spherical Linear Interpolation (Slerp)\nSince CLIP embeddings $s$ are normalized to a hypersphere, simple linear interpolation ($s_{interp} = (1-\\lambda)s_1 + \\lambda s_2$) would pull the interpolated vector inside the sphere, changing its norm and semantic \"intensity.\" Instead, we use Slerp:\n$$ \\Omega = \\arccos(s_A \\cdot s_B) $$\n$$ s_{interp}(\\gamma) = \\frac{\\sin((1-\\gamma)\\Omega)}{\\sin \\Omega} s_A + \\frac{\\sin(\\gamma \\Omega)}{\\sin \\Omega} s_B $$\nwhere $\\gamma \\in [0, 1]$ is the interpolation coefficient. This ensures that the interpolated semantic vector remains on the unit hypersphere, preserving the semantic coherence.\n\n### 3.5.2 Virtual Fault Synthesis and Manifold Consistency\nFor every pair of seen classes $(s_i, s_j) \\in \\mathcal{Y}_s$, we generate a set of virtual semantic embeddings $\\{s_{v,k}\\}$. These embeddings do not correspond to any known physical label but represent realistic \"transition\" states.\nBy feeding $s_{v,k}$ through the trained DPSD, we obtain virtual features $\\hat{x}_{v,k}$. We further enforce a manifold consistency constraint:\n$$ \\mathcal{L}_{SMI} = \\mathbb{E}_{\\gamma, s_A, s_B} [ \\| G(z, s_{interp}(\\gamma)) - \\text{Interp}(G(z, s_A), G(z, s_B), \\gamma) \\|_2^2 ] $$\nwhere $G$ is the generator and $\\text{Interp}$ is a feature-space interpolation function. This ensures that interpolation in the semantic space leads to smooth and predictable transitions in the feature space.\n\n**Benefits of SMI:**\n- **Boundary Clarification**: Helps the classifier learn more robust decision boundaries between fault types.\n- **Manifold Smoothing**: Reduces the \"gaps\" in the generative manifold, which is vital for generalizing to unseen classes that might lie between seen ones.\n- **Data Augmentation**: Provides a nearly infinite supply of diverse, semantically-grounded training data.\n\n## 3.6 Attribute Consistency Loss and Optimization\n\nTo ensure the physical validity of generated features, the model must be constrained by an explicit semantic feedback loop.\n\n### 3.6.1 The Semantic Regressor\nWe pre-train an attribute regressor $R: \\mathcal{X} \\to \\mathcal{S}$ using the real training data $\\mathcal{D}_{tr}$:\n$$ \\mathcal{L}_{R} = \\mathbb{E}_{(x, s) \\sim \\mathcal{D}_{tr}} [ \\| R(x) - s \\|_2^2 ] $$\nThe regressor $R$ is typically a deep neural network consisting of several 1D convolutional layers followed by global average pooling and a linear projection layer. Once trained, the weights of $R$ are frozen. This regressor acts as a \"critic\" that evaluates whether a generated feature $\\hat{x}$ actually contains the characteristics described by its input semantic $s$.\n\n### 3.6.2 Attribute Consistency Loss (ACL)\nDuring the training of the DPSD, we introduce the ACL to minimize the semantic reconstruction error:\n$$ \\mathcal{L}_{ACL} = \\mathbb{E}_{z, s} [ \\| R(G(z, s)) - s \\|_2^2 ] + \\lambda_{orth} \\mathcal{L}_{orth} $$\nThe second term $\\mathcal{L}_{orth}$ is an optional orthogonality constraint that encourages the regressor to learn independent semantic dimensions, preventing redundant attribute representation.\n\n### 3.6.3 Total Training Objective\nThe final loss function for the CESM-Diff model is a weighted sum of the diffusion noise prediction loss and the attribute consistency loss:\n$$ \\mathcal{L}_{total} = \\mathcal{L}_{diff} + \\eta \\mathcal{L}_{ACL} + \\sigma \\mathcal{L}_{SMI} $$\nwhere:\n$$ \\mathcal{L}_{diff} = \\mathbb{E}_{x_0, \\epsilon, t, s_0} [ \\| \\epsilon - \\epsilon_{\\theta}(\\sqrt{\\bar{\\alpha}_t} x_0 + \\sqrt{1-\\bar{\\alpha}_t} \\epsilon, s_0, t) \\|_2^2 ] $$\nThe hyperparameters $\\eta$ and $\\sigma$ control the strength of the semantic constraint and the interpolation consistency, respectively. In our experiments, we find that a relatively high $\\eta$ is necessary to prevent the model from generating \"mode-collapsed\" features that look like real sensor data but ignore the specific fault condition.\n\n### 3.6.4 Training and Generation Algorithm\n\nThe end-to-end training and inference pipeline follows a structured sequence of optimization and sampling. First, the semantic landscape is established through CLIP encoding and regressor pre-training. Then, the diffusion backbone is optimized to reconstruct features by conditioning on the noisy semantic paths. Finally, during the generation phase, the model synthesizes features for unseen classes by traversing the reverse diffusion path guided by corresponding CLIP-extracted semantic vectors.\n\n**Algorithm 1: CESM-Diff Training and Generation**\n---\n1. **Input**: Training data $\\{(x_i^s, y_i^s)\\}$, Text Prompts $\\{T_c\\}$, Pre-trained CLIP $E_{text}$, Iterations $N$, Guidance Scale $w$.\n2. **Setup Phase**:\n   - Extract semantic embeddings: $s_y = E_{text}(T_y)$ for all classes.\n   - Define noise schedules: Calculate $\\bar{\\alpha}_t$ and $\\beta_t$ variance schedules for $t=1 \\dots T$.\n   - Pre-train attribute regressor $R(x)$ to map features to CLIP semantics: $\\min \\mathcal{L}_R$.\n   - Initialize DPSD parameters $\\theta$.\n3. **Training Iterations**:\n   - **While** iteration $n < N$ **do**:\n     - Sample batch of real features $x_0 \\sim q(x_0)$.\n     - Sample random timesteps $t \\sim \\text{Uniform}(1, T)$.\n     - Sample Gaussian noise $\\epsilon \\sim \\mathcal{N}(0, \\mathbf{I})$ and $\\epsilon^s \\sim \\mathcal{N}(0, \\mathbf{I})$.\n     - Compute noisy feature $x_t = \\sqrt{\\bar{\\alpha}_t}x_0 + \\sqrt{1-\\bar{\\alpha}_t}\\epsilon$.\n     - Compute noisy semantic $s_t = \\sqrt{\\bar{\\alpha}_t^s}s_0 + \\sqrt{1-\\bar{\\alpha}_t^s}\\epsilon^s$.\n     - **Cross-Path Interaction**: Update $H_x$ via CPA attention with $H_s$.\n     - **Loss Computation**:\n       - Calculate noise prediction error: $\\mathcal{L}_{diff} = \\| \\epsilon - \\epsilon_{\\theta}(x_t, s_t, t) \\|^2$.\n       - (Every $k$ steps) Approximate $\\hat{x}_0 = \\frac{x_t - \\sqrt{1-\\bar{\\alpha}_t}\\epsilon_{\\theta}}{\\sqrt{\\bar{\\alpha}_t}}$ and compute $\\mathcal{L}_{ACL} = \\| R(\\hat{x}_0) - s_0 \\|^2$.\n       - Apply gradient descent on $\\nabla_{\\theta} (\\mathcal{L}_{diff} + \\eta \\mathcal{L}_{ACL})$.\n   - **End While**\n4. **Unseen Class Generation (Inference)**:\n   - For each unseen class $u \\in \\mathcal{Y}_u$:\n     - Retrieve semantic vector $s_u = E_{text}(T_u)$.\n     - Draw noise sample $z \\sim \\mathcal{N}(0, \\mathbf{I})$.\n     - Set $x_T = z$.\n     - **For** $t$ from $T$ down to 1:\n       - Predict noise $\\hat{\\epsilon} = (1+w) \\epsilon_{\\theta}(x_t, s_u, t) - w \\epsilon_{\\theta}(x_t, \\emptyset, t)$.\n       - Update $x_{t-1} = \\frac{1}{\\sqrt{\\alpha_t}} (x_t - \\frac{\\beta_t}{\\sqrt{1-\\bar{\\alpha}_t}}\\hat{\\epsilon}) + \\sigma_t z$.\n     - Store resulting feature $\\hat{x}_u$.\n5. **Downstream Classification**:\n   - Train a supervised classifier (e.g., Softmax, SVM, or Random Forest) using the combined dataset $\\{\\mathcal{D}_{tr} \\cup (\\hat{X}_u, \\mathcal{Y}_u)\\}$.\n\n---\n\nThrough this multi-stage methodology, the CESM-Diff model effectively learns to map the rich, natural-language-grounded semantic manifold of CLIP into the complex feature space of industrial machinery signals, enabling high-accuracy diagnosis of previously unseen failure modes. The integration of dual-path diffusion and attribute consistency ensures that the synthesized features are both physically realistic and semantically precise.\n"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1773714205761}}
