{"type":"message","id":"60db11e9","parentId":"d401b834","timestamp":"2026-03-17T03:00:40.595Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_64307a2f3313466db8c191fb","toolName":"exec","content":[{"type":"text","text":"--- Introduction 字数 & Flag ---\n650 /home/liaowenjie/.openclaw-multi/shared/paper-project-4/drafts/introduction.md\n/home/liaowenjie/.openclaw-multi/shared/paper-project-4/drafts/INTRODUCTION_V3_DONE.flag\nV3 flag ✅\n\n--- Writer 状态 ---\nHTTP 200\n--- All Agents ---\n  :18810 ✅\n  :18820 ✅\n  :18830 ✅\n  :18840 ✅\n  :18850 ✅\n  :18860 ✅\n  :18870 ✅"}],"details":{"status":"completed","exitCode":0,"durationMs":37,"aggregated":"--- Introduction 字数 & Flag ---\n650 /home/liaowenjie/.openclaw-multi/shared/paper-project-4/drafts/introduction.md\n/home/liaowenjie/.openclaw-multi/shared/paper-project-4/drafts/INTRODUCTION_V3_DONE.flag\nV3 flag ✅\n\n--- Writer 状态 ---\nHTTP 200\n--- All Agents ---\n  :18810 ✅\n  :18820 ✅\n  :18830 ✅\n  :18840 ✅\n  :18850 ✅\n  :18860 ✅\n  :18870 ✅","cwd":"/home/liaowenjie/.openclaw-multi/leader/workspace"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1773716440593}}
{"type":"message","id":"1c644291","parentId":"60db11e9","timestamp":"2026-03-17T03:00:55.951Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Interesting! The Introduction is now 650 words, which is even lower than before (was 1526). The Writer seems to have over-corrected - it went from 1526 to 650 words, which is now too short (target is 900-1500 for ±25% tolerance around 1200).Let me check what's in the Introduction file to understand what happened.\n","thinkingSignature":"reasoning"},{"type":"text","text":"⚠️ **Introduction 出问题了！**\n\n- 上轮：1526 词（超出容差 +27%）\n- 本轮：**650 词**（不足容差 -46%！）\n- 目标：900-1500 词（1200 ±25%）\n\nWriter **精简过度**了，从超长变成了太短。需要重新扩充约 250-300 词。\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_1a780bfe91ae4d22a89c428f","name":"read","arguments":{"file_path":"/home/liaowenjie/.openclaw-multi/shared/paper-project-4/drafts/introduction.md"}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"openrouter","model":"minimax/minimax-m2.5","usage":{"input":82760,"output":284,"cacheRead":256,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":83300,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1773716440595}}
{"type":"message","id":"cb1f6a46","parentId":"1c644291","timestamp":"2026-03-17T03:00:55.955Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_1a780bfe91ae4d22a89c428f","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"# Introduction\n\nIndustrial fault diagnosis is essential for the safety and efficiency of modern manufacturing in the Industry 4.0 era. As processes grow more complex and automated, mechanical failures can lead to significant economic losses or catastrophic accidents. Consequently, traditional time-based maintenance is being replaced by data-driven intelligent systems that leverage Industrial Internet of Things (IIoT) sensor data for real-time health monitoring.\n\nWhile deep learning techniques like CNNs, RNNs, and Transformers have revolutionized automated fault detection by extracting features from raw signals, they fundamentally rely on a \"closed-world\" assumption. These models require vast amounts of labeled training data for every possible fault class—a requirement that is often impractical in real-world environments where collecting comprehensive, balanced fault data is nearly impossible. This scarcity stems from several factors: high-stability systems (e.g., turbines, nuclear plants) cannot be operated under faulty conditions for data collection; degradation processes in components like bearings often span months or years; and simulated \"fault injection\" in labs often fails to capture the noise of actual industrial settings. These constraints have driven research into Zero-Shot Fault Diagnosis (ZSFD).\n\nZSFD decouples dependency on labeled samples by representing fault types in a high-dimensional semantic space, using attributes or natural language to bridge \"seen\" and \"unseen\" classes. By transferring patterns—such as the relationship between vibration frequencies and specific component failures—ZSFD allows models to generalize to faults never encountered during training. Recent advancements have utilized generative models like GANs, VAEs, and Denoising Diffusion Probabilistic Models (DDPMs) to synthesize representative features for unseen classes based on semantic descriptions, thereby converting zero-shot tasks into supervised learning problems.\n\nDespite this progress, current ZSFD approaches face critical bottlenecks. Most rely on manual, discrete attributes (e.g., binary vectors) that fail to capture the nuanced, continuous nature of physical fault progression. This creates \"semantic gaps\" where predefined attributes do not align with physical data distributions. Furthermore, existing methods often suffer from \"domain shift,\" where mappings learned in the seen space fail to generalize to the unseen space. Most models also lack the flexibility to handle intermediate or hybrid fault states that do not fit into fixed categories, limiting their reliability in dynamic industrial systems.\n\nTo address these challenges, this paper proposes the CLIP-Enhanced Semantic Manifold Diffusion (CESM-Diff) model. Moving beyond manual engineering, we leverage the CLIP (Contrastive Language-Image Pre-training) text encoder to extract continuous semantic embeddings from natural language fault descriptions. This transforms discrete attributes into a continuous semantic manifold that captures rich physical context. Our architecture introduces a dual-path diffusion mechanism that simultaneously processes feature-level information and semantic embeddings, using cross-path attention to align text-based knowledge with signal-based features. Additionally, we propose a Semantic Manifold Interpolation (SMI) mechanism, enabling the model to perform \"topological reasoning\" to diagnose intermediate or emerging fault conditions.\n\nThe main contributions of this paper are summarized as follows:\n\n1) We propose the CLIP-Enhanced Semantic Manifold Diffusion (CESM-Diff) framework, which replaces labor-intensive manual labeling with continuous semantic embeddings derived from natural language. This narrows the semantic gap between physical signals and human expertise.\n\n2) We design a dual-path diffusion mechanism with feature-based and semantic-based paths. Coupled with cross-path attention, this architecture enables robust interaction between levels, enhancing the generation of physically realistic features for unseen classes and mitigating domain shift.\n\n3) We introduce the Semantic Manifold Interpolation (SMI) mechanism. By leveraging CLIP-based semantic continuity, SMI allows the model to hypothesize and handle transitions between known states, providing a sound approach for diagnosing \"in-between\" fault conditions.\n\n4) We conduct extensive evaluations on the Tennessee Eastman Process (TEP), Hydraulic System, and CWRU Bearing datasets. Results show that CESM-Diff consistently outperforms state-of-the-art ZSFD approaches across metrics including Acc-S, Acc-U, and H-measure.\n\nThe remainder of this paper is organized as follows: Section II reviews related work in zero-shot learning and generative models. Section III details the CESM-Diff methodology, including CLIP embedding and the SMI mechanism. Section IV presents the experimental setup and results analysis, and Section V concludes the paper.\n"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1773716455953}}
