{"type":"message","id":"38f13663","parentId":"8c78e92c","timestamp":"2026-03-17T05:15:05.853Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"日志显示 Editor 有 \"Network connection lost\" 错误，这说明 Editor 也遇到了和 Writer 一样的问题 - Claude 代理的输出长度限制或其他问题导致任务失败。\n\n根据 Project 3 的经验，当 Editor 不可靠时，Leader 应该直接接管。让我直接创建 paper.tex 文件。\n","thinkingSignature":"reasoning"},{"type":"text","text":"⚠️ **Editor 失败** — 日志显示 \"Network connection lost\"，和之前 Writer 的问题一样。\n\n**解决方案：Leader 直接接管创建 paper.tex**\n\n让我快速整合：\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_a7879c703f0b45e6bb678cc6","name":"read","arguments":{"file_path":"/home/liaowenjie/.openclaw-multi/shared/paper-project-4/drafts/introduction.md","limit":30}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"openrouter","model":"minimax/minimax-m2.5","usage":{"input":1084,"output":215,"cacheRead":117504,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":118803,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1773724498714}}
{"type":"message","id":"ce2072b0","parentId":"38f13663","timestamp":"2026-03-17T05:15:05.858Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_a7879c703f0b45e6bb678cc6","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"# Introduction\n\nIndustrial fault diagnosis has emerged as a cornerstone of modern industrial operations, serving as an indispensable safeguard for the safety, reliability, and efficiency of manufacturing processes in the era of Industry 4.0. As industrial systems grow increasingly complex, interconnected, and automated, the stakes for maintaining system integrity have never been higher. According to recent industrial surveys, unexpected equipment downtime can cost large-scale manufacturing facilities up to $20,000 per minute, with annual global losses estimated in the billions. Beyond economic impact, mechanical failures in critical sectors such as aerospace, nuclear power generation, and chemical processing can lead to catastrophic environmental disasters and loss of human life. Consequently, the paradigm of industrial maintenance is undergoing a fundamental shift from traditional reactive \"run-to-failure\" models toward data-driven, intelligent condition-based monitoring systems that leverage the vast streams of data generated by the Industrial Internet of Things (IIoT).\n\nThe primary objective of intelligent fault diagnosis is to automatically interpret complex sensor signals—such as vibration, acoustic emission, and pressure—to detect anomalies and identify specific failure modes. In recent years, deep learning (DL) architectures, including Convolutional Neural Networks (CNNs) and Transformers, have revolutionized this field. These models excel at extracting hierarchical features directly from raw, non-stationary signals, bypassing the need for expert-dependent manual feature engineering. By learning high-level abstractions, DL models have achieved human-level accuracy in identifying known fault categories within controlled environments.\n\nHowever, the transition of deep learning models from laboratory settings to real-world industrial floors reveals a fundamental flaw: they operate under a rigid \"closed-world\" assumption. This assumption presupposes that all possible fault classes are known beforehand and that the training dataset contains representative distribution of labeled samples for every category. In practice, this requirement is almost never met. Industrial environments are characterized by an inherent \"data scarcity\" trap. High-stability systems, such as steam turbines or nuclear coolant pumps, are designed to operate without failure for decades. Consequently, while \"normal\" operating data is abundant, actual failure data is exceedingly rare. It is often economically impossible to intentionally run critical machinery to failure just to collect training data. While laboratory simulations provide some relief, the resulting data often fails to capture the complex noise profiles and load variations present in actual industrial settings. This creates a \"long-tail\" distribution where most potential failure modes remain \"unseen\" during the model's training phase.\n\nThe limitations of supervised learning under these constraints have catalyzed the development of Zero-Shot Fault Diagnosis (ZSFD). ZSFD aims to decouple the dependency on labeled physical samples for every class by representing fault types in a high-dimensional semantic space. By using side information—such as expert-defined attributes or natural language descriptions—ZSFD creates a bridge between \"seen\" classes (those with training data) and \"unseen\" classes (those known only by description). This allows the model to transfer knowledge: if the model understands the relationship between specific frequencies and bearing defects in one machine, it should theoretically be able to diagnose a similar defect in an unseen component based on its semantic profile. Recent advancements in ZSFD have moved toward generative frameworks like GANs, VAEs, and Denoising Diffusion Probabilistic Models (DDPMs), which can synthesize pseudo-features for unseen classes directly from their semantic embeddings.\n\nDespite these breakthroughs, current ZSFD methodologies face critical bottlenecks that prevent their widespread industrial adoption:\n\n1) **The Semantic Representation Bottleneck**: Most existing models rely on manually engineered, discrete attribute vectors—often binary indicators representing the presence or absence of specific properties. These rigid vectors fail to capture the nuanced, continuous, and overlapping nature of physical fault progression. A bearing defect evolves through a spectrum of severity, and discrete attributes provide a coarse, low-resolution view that ignores this vital context.\n\n2) **Domain Shift and Alignment Challenge**: The mapping from the semantic space to the physical feature space is typically learned using only \"seen\" classes. Because the distribution of features for unseen faults may differ significantly from the training data, the model often produces \"biased\" generations that gravitate toward the seen classes, leading to poor diagnostic accuracy for truly novel faults.\n\n3) **Lack of Topological Flexibility**: Industrial systems are dynamic; faults can be hybrid or intermediate. Current ZSFD models generally treat fault diagnosis as a N-way classification among fixed points, lacking the ability to reason about the \"in-between\" states on the semantic manifold. \n\nFurthermore, the reliance on manual attributes introduces a high degree of subjectivity and labor cost. Defining a comprehensive attribute set for complex processes requires weeks of consultation with domain experts, making the system difficult to scale. There is an urgent need for a framework that can absorb \"live\" expert knowledge in its most natural form—language—while maintaining the mathematical rigor required for high-accuracy feature synthesis.\n\nTo address these challenges, this paper introduces the CLIP-Enhanced Semantic Manifold Diffusion (CESM-Diff) model. Our approach represents a paradigm shift in how semantic information is integrated into fault diagnosis. Rather than relying on static, hand-coded vectors, we leverage the pre-trained CLIP (Contrastive Language-Image Pre-training) text encoder to extract continuous, high-dimensional semantic embeddings from natural language descriptions. This transforms the discrete attribute space into a continuous \"semantic manifold\" that inherently encodes the physical relationships between different fault states.\n\nThe architecture of CESM-Diff is built upon a dual-path diffusion mechanism. Unlike standard generative models that only diffuse the physical feature space, our model features a synchronized semantic path. The two paths interact through a novel cross-path attention mechanism, ensuring that the generated features are \"semantically grounded.\" This dual-layer approach effectively mitigates domain shift by forcing the model to learn the underlying manifold structure. Furthermore, we propose a Semantic Manifold Interpolation (SMI) mechanism. By treating the CLIP-based semantic space as a continuous manifold, SMI enables the model to perform \"topological reasoning.\" This allows CESM-Diff to hypothesize and synthesize features for \"intermediate\" states that were never explicitly defined, providing a robust solution for diagnosing emerging fault conditions.\n\nThe main contributions of this paper are summarized as follows:\n\n1) We propose the CLIP-Enhanced Semantic Manifold Diffusion (CESM-Diff) framework, which marks the first integration of large-scale contrastive language models with diffusion-based generative diagnosis. By replacing labor-intensive manual attribute engineering with continuous semantic embeddings derived from natural language, we significantly narrow the \"semantic gap\" between raw physical signals and human expert knowledge.\n\n2) We design a dual-path diffusion mechanism that simultaneously processes physical signal features and semantic embeddings. This architecture, coupled with a cross-path attention module, enables bi-directional interaction between the data and the description. This interaction ensures the generation of physically realistic features for unseen classes, effectively mitigating the common issue of domain shift and bias toward seen classes.\n\n\n[6 more lines in file. Use offset=31 to continue.]"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1773724505854}}
