{"type":"message","id":"dd510826","parentId":"81e5acc1","timestamp":"2026-03-17T07:14:21.244Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_3fa935781fe24ea59447c23e","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"# LaTeX 格式审查报告\n\n## 审查结论：MAJOR REVISION\n\n## 一、编译检查\n\n### 1.1 编译状态：❌ 存在错误\n\n| 项目 | 状态 | 说明 |\n|------|------|------|\n| pdflatex 编译 | ❌ 错误 | `Missing $ inserted` 在 introduction.tex 第4行 |\n| 编译输出 | ⚠️ 部分成功 | 生成14页PDF，但有致命错误阻止完整编译 |\n| .bbl 文件 | ❌ 缺失 | 提示 \"No file paper.bbl\" |\n\n### 1.2 具体编译错误\n\n1. **致命错误 (introduction.tex line 4)**\n   ```\n   ! Missing $ inserted.\n   <inserted text> \n                   $\n   l.4 \n   ```\n   原因：可能在第一段中存在未转义的特殊字符（如下划线 `_` 或 `&`）\n\n2. **Runaway argument 错误 (experiments.tex line 37)**\n   ```\n   Runaway argument?\n   {8.7\\par \\subsubsection {2) Performance on Hydraulic System} \\par The\\ETC.\n   ! File ended while scanning use of \\textbf .\n   ```\n   原因：`\\textbf{Table II}` 中的 `8.7%` 包含 `%` 符号，需要转义为 `\\%`\n\n3. **Bibliography 错误**\n   - 缺少 `.bbl` 文件（需要运行 bibtex）\n   - 多个引用未定义：\n     - `lampert2009`, `feng2020`, `chen2021`, `hu2022`\n     - `xing2022`, `song2025`, `lv2021`, `zhuo2022`\n     - `guo2023`, `wang2024`, `radford2021`, `wang2025`\n\n---\n\n## 二、图片引用格式检查\n\n### 2.1 状态：❌ 需要修复\n\n| 当前格式 | 正确格式 | 位置 |\n|----------|----------|------|\n| `Fig. 1` | `\\figref{1}` 或 `Figure~\\ref{fig:1}` | experiments.tex:20 |\n| `(Fig. 2)` | `(Figure~\\ref{fig:2})` | experiments.tex:38 |\n| `\\textbf Fig. 4}` | `\\textbf{Figure~\\ref{fig:4}}` | experiments.tex:122-125 |\n| `\\textbf Fig. 5}` | `\\textbf{Figure~\\ref{fig:5}}` | experiments.tex:134 |\n| `\\textbf Fig. 6}` | `\\textbf{Figure~\\ref{fig:6}}` | experiments.tex:138 |\n| `\\textbf Fig. 1}` | `\\textbf{Figure~\\ref{fig:1}}` | methodology.tex:55 |\n| `\\textbf Fig. 2}` | `\\textbf{Figure~\\ref{fig:2}}` | methodology.tex:74 |\n| `\\textbf Fig. 3}` | `\\textbf{Figure~\\ref{fig:3}}` | methodology.tex:112 |\n\n### 2.2 修复建议\n\n1. **添加图表标签定义**：在 figures 环境中添加 `\\label{fig:X}`\n2. **统一引用格式**：使用 `Figure~\\ref{fig:X}` 或自定义命令 `\\figref{X}`\n3. **移除手动格式**：将所有 `Fig. X` 替换为正确格式\n\n---\n\n## 三、表格引用格式检查\n\n### 3.1 状态：⚠️ 部分正确，仍需改进\n\n| 当前格式 | 建议格式 | 位置 |\n|----------|----------|------|\n| `Table I` | `Table~\\ref{tab:notation}` | methodology.tex:23 |\n| `Table II` | `Table~\\ref{tab:tep_results}` | experiments.tex:89 |\n| `\\textbf{Table II}` | `\\textbf{Table~\\ref{tab:tep_results}}` | experiments.tex:100 |\n| `Table III` | `Table~\\ref{tab:hydraulic_results}` | experiments.tex:104 |\n| `Table IV` | `Table~\\ref{tab:cwru_results}` | experiments.tex:116 |\n| `\\textbf{Table V}` | `\\textbf{Table~\\ref{tab:ablation}}` | experiments.tex:146 |\n\n### 3.2 修复建议\n\n1. 为所有表格添加 `\\label{tab:xxx}`\n2. 统一使用 `Table~\\ref{tab:xxx}` 格式\n3. 检查是否有表格 caption 缺失\n\n---\n\n## 四、公式格式检查\n\n### 4.1 状态：✅ 大部分正确\n\n公式使用标准 `amsmath` 格式，包括：\n- 行内公式 `$...$`\n- 行间公式 `\\[ ... \\]`\n- 编号公式 `\\begin{equation}`\n\n**注意**：检查 methodology.tex 中的公式是否有显示问题\n\n---\n\n## 五、参考文献格式检查\n\n### 5.1 状态：❌ 存在严重问题\n\n#### 问题 1：Citation Key 不匹配\n\n| 文中使用的 Citation | references.bib 中的 Key |\n|---------------------|-------------------------|\n| `\\cite{lampert2009}` | ❌ 不存在 |\n| `\\cite{feng2020}` | ❌ 不存在 |\n| `\\cite{chen2021}` | ❌ 不存在 |\n| `\\cite{hu2022}` | ❌ 不存在 |\n| `\\cite{xing2022}` | ❌ 不存在 |\n| `\\cite{song2025}` | ❌ 不存在 |\n| `\\cite{lv2021}` | ❌ 不存在 |\n| `\\cite{zhuo2022}` | ❌ 不存在 |\n| `\\cite{guo2023}` | ❌ 不存在 |\n| `\\cite{wang2024}` | ❌ 不存在 (只有 wang2024federated) |\n| `\\cite{wang2025}` | ❌ 不存在 |\n| `\\cite{ho2020}` | 存在，但 key 是 `ho2020ddpm` |\n| `\\cite{radford2021}` | 存在，但 key 是 `radford2021clip` |\n\n#### 问题 2： Bibliography 未生成\n\n需要运行以下命令序列：\n```bash\npdflatex paper.tex\nbibtex paper.aux\npdflatex paper.tex\npdflatex paper.tex\n```\n\n---\n\n## 六、具体修复清单\n\n### 🔴 必须修复（阻塞性错误）\n\n1. **修复 introduction.tex 第4行的 $ 缺失错误**\n   - 检查并修复未转义的特殊字符\n\n2. **修复 experiments.tex 中的 % 符号**\n   - 将 `8.7%` 改为 `8.7\\%`\n   - 将所有类似 `82.3%` 改为 `82.3\\%`\n\n3. **修复 citation key 不匹配问题**\n   - 更新 `related_work.tex` 中的所有 citation key\n   - 或在 `references.bib` 中添加缺失的引用\n\n4. **生成 bibliography**\n   - 运行 bibtex 编译流程\n\n### 🟡 建议修复（格式规范）\n\n5. **统一图片引用格式**\n   - 创建 `\\figref` 命令或使用 `Figure~\\ref{}`\n   - 示例：`Figure~\\ref{fig:architecture}`\n\n6. **统一表格引用格式**\n   - 使用 `Table~\\ref{}` 格式\n\n7. **为所有图表添加 label**\n   - 确保每个 figure 和 table 都有 `\\label{}`\n\n---\n\n## 七、编译命令\n\n请按以下顺序执行：\n\n```bash\ncd /home/liaowenjie/.openclaw-multi/shared/paper-project-4/final\n\n# 第一次编译\npdflatex -interaction=nonstopmode paper.tex\n\n# 生成参考文献\nbibtex paper.aux\n\n# 第二次编译\npdflatex -interaction=nonstopmode paper.tex\n\n# 第三次编译（解决交叉引用）\npdflatex -interaction=nonstopmode paper.tex\n```\n\n---\n\n## 审查人：Reviewer Agent\n审查时间：2026-03-17\n"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1773731661240}}
{"type":"message","id":"8bcc052b","parentId":"dd510826","timestamp":"2026-03-17T07:14:50.386Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Checker 发现了 MAJOR REVISION 级别的问题：\n\n1. 编译错误 - introduction.tex 和 experiments.tex 有特殊字符问题\n2. Citation key 不匹配 - 很多引用 key 与 references.bib 不一致3. 图片/表格引用格式需要修复让我修复这些问题。\n","thinkingSignature":"reasoning"},{"type":"text","text":"⚠️ **Checker 审查结果：MAJOR REVISION**\n\n### 问题汇总\n\n| 类型 | 问题 |\n|------|------|\n| ❌ 编译错误 | introduction.tex 有未转义字符，experiments.tex 有 % 符号 |\n| ❌ Citation key | 多个引用 key 与 references.bib 不匹配 |\n| ❌ 引用格式 | 图片/表格引用未使用 \\ref{} 格式 |\n\n开始修复（Round 1）：\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_358da3d0483f4cbeafe99907","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"SHARED=\"/home/liaowenjie/.openclaw-multi/shared/paper-project-4\"\n\n# 1. 修复 % 符号（在 .md 文件中）\nsed -i 's/\\([0-9]\\)%\\([ ,.]\\)/\\1\\\\%\\2/g' \"$SHARED/drafts/experiments.md\"\nsed -i 's/\\([0-9]\\)%$/\\1\\\\%/g' \"$SHARED/drafts/experiments.md\"\necho \"✅ 修复 % 符号\"\n\n# 2. 检查 introduction 第一段\nhead -10 \"$SHARED/drafts/introduction.md\"","timeout":10}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"openrouter","model":"minimax/minimax-m2.5","usage":{"input":142862,"output":394,"cacheRead":1600,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":144856,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1773731661244}}
{"type":"message","id":"dd49b8d2","parentId":"8bcc052b","timestamp":"2026-03-17T07:14:50.401Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_358da3d0483f4cbeafe99907","toolName":"exec","content":[{"type":"text","text":"✅ 修复 % 符号\n# Introduction\n\nIndustrial fault diagnosis has emerged as a cornerstone of modern industrial operations, serving as an indispensable safeguard for the safety, reliability, and efficiency of manufacturing processes in the era of Industry 4.0. As industrial systems grow increasingly complex, interconnected, and automated, the stakes for maintaining system integrity have never been higher. According to recent industrial surveys, unexpected equipment downtime can cost large-scale manufacturing facilities up to $20,000 per minute, with annual global losses estimated in the billions. Beyond economic impact, mechanical failures in critical sectors such as aerospace, nuclear power generation, and chemical processing can lead to catastrophic environmental disasters and loss of human life. Consequently, the paradigm of industrial maintenance is undergoing a fundamental shift from traditional reactive \"run-to-failure\" models toward data-driven, intelligent condition-based monitoring systems that leverage the vast streams of data generated by the Industrial Internet of Things (IIoT).\n\nThe primary objective of intelligent fault diagnosis is to automatically interpret complex sensor signals—such as vibration, acoustic emission, and pressure—to detect anomalies and identify specific failure modes. In recent years, deep learning (DL) architectures, including Convolutional Neural Networks (CNNs) and Transformers, have revolutionized this field. These models excel at extracting hierarchical features directly from raw, non-stationary signals, bypassing the need for expert-dependent manual feature engineering. By learning high-level abstractions, DL models have achieved human-level accuracy in identifying known fault categories within controlled environments.\n\nHowever, the transition of deep learning models from laboratory settings to real-world industrial floors reveals a fundamental flaw: they operate under a rigid \"closed-world\" assumption. This assumption presupposes that all possible fault classes are known beforehand and that the training dataset contains representative distribution of labeled samples for every category. In practice, this requirement is almost never met. Industrial environments are characterized by an inherent \"data scarcity\" trap. High-stability systems, such as steam turbines or nuclear coolant pumps, are designed to operate without failure for decades. Consequently, while \"normal\" operating data is abundant, actual failure data is exceedingly rare. It is often economically impossible to intentionally run critical machinery to failure just to collect training data. While laboratory simulations provide some relief, the resulting data often fails to capture the complex noise profiles and load variations present in actual industrial settings. This creates a \"long-tail\" distribution where most potential failure modes remain \"unseen\" during the model's training phase.\n\nThe limitations of supervised learning under these constraints have catalyzed the development of Zero-Shot Fault Diagnosis (ZSFD). ZSFD aims to decouple the dependency on labeled physical samples for every class by representing fault types in a high-dimensional semantic space. By using side information—such as expert-defined attributes or natural language descriptions—ZSFD creates a bridge between \"seen\" classes (those with training data) and \"unseen\" classes (those known only by description). This allows the model to transfer knowledge: if the model understands the relationship between specific frequencies and bearing defects in one machine, it should theoretically be able to diagnose a similar defect in an unseen component based on its semantic profile. Recent advancements in ZSFD have moved toward generative frameworks like GANs, VAEs, and Denoising Diffusion Probabilistic Models (DDPMs), which can synthesize pseudo-features for unseen classes directly from their semantic embeddings."}],"details":{"status":"completed","exitCode":0,"durationMs":7,"aggregated":"✅ 修复 % 符号\n# Introduction\n\nIndustrial fault diagnosis has emerged as a cornerstone of modern industrial operations, serving as an indispensable safeguard for the safety, reliability, and efficiency of manufacturing processes in the era of Industry 4.0. As industrial systems grow increasingly complex, interconnected, and automated, the stakes for maintaining system integrity have never been higher. According to recent industrial surveys, unexpected equipment downtime can cost large-scale manufacturing facilities up to $20,000 per minute, with annual global losses estimated in the billions. Beyond economic impact, mechanical failures in critical sectors such as aerospace, nuclear power generation, and chemical processing can lead to catastrophic environmental disasters and loss of human life. Consequently, the paradigm of industrial maintenance is undergoing a fundamental shift from traditional reactive \"run-to-failure\" models toward data-driven, intelligent condition-based monitoring systems that leverage the vast streams of data generated by the Industrial Internet of Things (IIoT).\n\nThe primary objective of intelligent fault diagnosis is to automatically interpret complex sensor signals—such as vibration, acoustic emission, and pressure—to detect anomalies and identify specific failure modes. In recent years, deep learning (DL) architectures, including Convolutional Neural Networks (CNNs) and Transformers, have revolutionized this field. These models excel at extracting hierarchical features directly from raw, non-stationary signals, bypassing the need for expert-dependent manual feature engineering. By learning high-level abstractions, DL models have achieved human-level accuracy in identifying known fault categories within controlled environments.\n\nHowever, the transition of deep learning models from laboratory settings to real-world industrial floors reveals a fundamental flaw: they operate under a rigid \"closed-world\" assumption. This assumption presupposes that all possible fault classes are known beforehand and that the training dataset contains representative distribution of labeled samples for every category. In practice, this requirement is almost never met. Industrial environments are characterized by an inherent \"data scarcity\" trap. High-stability systems, such as steam turbines or nuclear coolant pumps, are designed to operate without failure for decades. Consequently, while \"normal\" operating data is abundant, actual failure data is exceedingly rare. It is often economically impossible to intentionally run critical machinery to failure just to collect training data. While laboratory simulations provide some relief, the resulting data often fails to capture the complex noise profiles and load variations present in actual industrial settings. This creates a \"long-tail\" distribution where most potential failure modes remain \"unseen\" during the model's training phase.\n\nThe limitations of supervised learning under these constraints have catalyzed the development of Zero-Shot Fault Diagnosis (ZSFD). ZSFD aims to decouple the dependency on labeled physical samples for every class by representing fault types in a high-dimensional semantic space. By using side information—such as expert-defined attributes or natural language descriptions—ZSFD creates a bridge between \"seen\" classes (those with training data) and \"unseen\" classes (those known only by description). This allows the model to transfer knowledge: if the model understands the relationship between specific frequencies and bearing defects in one machine, it should theoretically be able to diagnose a similar defect in an unseen component based on its semantic profile. Recent advancements in ZSFD have moved toward generative frameworks like GANs, VAEs, and Denoising Diffusion Probabilistic Models (DDPMs), which can synthesize pseudo-features for unseen classes directly from their semantic embeddings.","cwd":"/home/liaowenjie/.openclaw-multi/leader/workspace"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1773731690396}}
